!! TiddlyWiki MCP Server

The MCP (Model Context Protocol) server lets AI assistants like Claude, Gemini, and others interact with your TiddlyWiki. It exposes wiki operations as tools over stdio and named pipe transports.

!! What It Does

* ''Read'' tiddlers, search with filters, render wikitext content
* ''Inspect'' TiddlyWiki's internal `$tw` object structure and function source code
* ''Render'' arbitrary wikitext snippets with full macro/procedure support
* ''Create'' and ''update'' tiddlers with automatic timestamps
* ''Edit'' specific lines using hash-validated references (token-efficient)
* ''Delete'' tiddlers and their files on disk
* ''Upload'' binary files (images, PDFs) via the `tw-upload` helper
* ''Export'' your wiki as HTML or a wiki folder

!! Quick Start

```
cd /your/wiki/dir
tiddlywiki . --mcp
```

To connect an AI client, see [[MCP Installation]] for `.mcp.json` setup (Claude Code) and [[MCP Gemini Configuration]] for Gemini CLI.

!! Filesystem Plugin

The MCP server requires the `tiddlywiki/filesystem` plugin for disk persistence. The `--mcp` command ''auto-loads'' it if not already present in your `tiddlywiki.info` — no need to add `+plugins/tiddlywiki/filesystem` to your command line.

!! Transports

The MCP server runs ''two transports simultaneously'':

* ''stdio'' — standard input/output, used by Claude CLI and other MCP clients
* ''Named pipe'' — local IPC for helper tools like `tw-upload`. A `.tw-mcp/connect` discovery file is written to the canonical wiki directory containing the pipe path, auth token, server PID, and label (if set).

!! Proxy Mode and Takeover

When multiple MCP processes target the same wiki, only the first becomes the ''primary'' (owns `$tw.wiki` and the named pipe). Subsequent processes automatically run as ''proxies'', relaying all JSON-RPC calls through the pipe to the primary.

When a proxy also runs an HTTP server (`--mcp listen`), it automatically takes over as primary. This ensures browser edits and MCP tool calls share the same `$tw.wiki` store — changes are visible instantly in both directions without `reload_tiddlers`.

```
tiddlywiki ./editions/tw5.com --mcp label=claude
tiddlywiki ./editions/tw5.com-server --mcp listen label=listen
```

After takeover, `label=listen` is the primary and `label=claude` becomes a proxy. See [[MCP Proxy Mode Concept]] for details.

!! Shared State

When `--mcp` and `--listen` run in the same process, they expose shared state on `$tw`:

* `$tw.mcp` — MCP server info: `pid`, `role`, `label`, `readonly`, `heartbeat()`
* `$tw.httpServer` — HTTP server info: `server`, `nodeServer`, `heartbeat()`

Both are queryable via the `inspect_tw` tool. The `get_wiki_info` tool also reports their status.

!! Safety Features

* ''Metadata by default'' — tiddler queries return all fields except `text` to save tokens. Use `detailed=true` to include text content.
* ''Token efficiency'' — tool results are returned as pre-formatted plain text, not JSON. This reduces token usage by ~3× compared to structured JSON responses.
* ''Namespace summaries'' — large result sets are automatically grouped by prefix with counts, allowing progressive drill-down instead of flooding with thousands of titles.
* ''System tiddler exclusion'' — system tiddlers (`$:/` prefix) and shadow tiddlers are excluded from results by default. They are only returned when explicitly requested.
* ''Filter optimization'' — the AI is instructed to always put `!is[system]` first in filter expressions to reduce the working set early.
* ''Overwrite protection'' — existing tiddlers are not overwritten unless explicitly confirmed. A new unique title is generated instead (like the ~TiddlyWiki ~CreateTiddler widget).
* ''Readonly by default'' — the server starts in readonly mode. Use `--mcp rw` to enable write operations.
* ''Path restrictions'' — file operations are restricted to the wiki's `tiddlers/`, `files/`, and `output/` directories.
* ''Pipe authentication'' — named pipe connections require a cryptographic token (256-bit random hex). The token is stored in the owner-only `.tw-mcp/connect` file.
* ''Confirmation prompts'' — the AI is instructed to confirm before bulk changes.
* ''Timestamps'' — `created` and `modified` fields are managed automatically, respecting `$:/config/TimestampDisable`.

!! Available Tools

!!! Read tools

|!Tool |!Keywords |!Description |
|`get_tiddler` |show, read, get |Get a tiddler's metadata by title (set `detailed=true` for full text with hashline anchors, `format='tid'` for plain text) |
|`list_tiddlers` |list, browse, tagged with |List tiddler titles, optionally filtered by tag or browse plugin contents |
|`run_filter` |find, search, how many |Run a TiddlyWiki filter expression |
|`render_tiddler` |render, display, preview |Render a tiddler to plain text or HTML (with full macro support) |
|`render_text` |render wikitext, test, try |Render arbitrary wikitext with full context (macros, procedures, variables), or output the parse tree |
|`render_field` |render field, preview field |Render a single tiddler field or data index as wikitext |
|`inspect_tree` |widget tree, structure |Analyze the rendered widget tree: type counts, link targets, transclusion tracking |
|`inspect_pos` |where from, source, trace |Render wikitext to HTML with source position attributes tracing each element to its source tiddler and line range |
|`inspect_scope` |variables, scope, params |Inspect the variable scope at a specific source position (procedure params, let bindings, globals) |
|`inspect_tw` |inspect $tw, internal |Inspect TiddlyWiki's internal `$tw` object structure and function source code |
|`get_wiki_info` |wiki info, plugins, settings |Get wiki metadata, tiddler counts, plugins, and basic settings |
|`reload_tiddlers` |reload, refresh, sync |Refresh in-memory store from disk + report changes since last call |

!!! Write tools (require `rw` mode)

|!Tool |!Keywords |!Description |
|`put_tiddler` |create, new tiddler, write |Create or update a tiddler |
|`edit_tiddler` |edit, change, update, fix |Edit specific lines using hashline references — token-efficient, with automatic conflict detection |
|`delete_tiddler` |delete, remove |Delete a tiddler and its file |
|`upload_file` |upload, attach, add image |Upload a base64-encoded binary file and create a canonical tiddler |
|`save_wiki_folder` |export, save as folder |Export wiki as a folder structure |
|`build_wiki` |build, export HTML |Render wiki as a single HTML file |

For the full keyword list and prompt tips, see [[MCP Best Practices]].

!! Helper Tools

!!! `tw-upload`

A standalone CLI tool for uploading binary files (PNG, JPG, GIF, PDF) to a running MCP server via named pipe:

```
node tw-upload.js photo.png --wiki ./wiki --title "My Photo" --tags "images"
```

The MCP server must be running. See [[MCP Upload Tool]] for details.

For detailed usage of each tool, see [[MCP Instructions]].

For a comprehensive guide to exploring `$tw` internals, see [[MCP Inspect Tool]].

For source position tracking and the `inspect_pos`/`inspect_scope`/`inspect_tree` workflow, see [[MCP Source Position Tracking]].

For proxy mode, takeover, and multi-process architecture, see [[MCP Proxy Mode Concept]].